A Road Safety Audit for Five Corners in the Town of Easton was held on December 21, 2009 at the
Easton Town Hall. Five Corners is the intersection of Foundry Street (Route 106/123), Depot Street
(Route 123) and Bay Road. As indicated in Table 1, the audit team consisted of representatives from
Federal, State, Regional and Local agencies and included a cross-section of engineering, planning,
DPW Operations Manager, Town of Easton
The Federal Highway Administration defines a Road Safety Audit (RSA) as the formal safety
examination of an existing or future road or intersection by an independent, multidisciplinary team. The
purpose of an RSA is to identify potential safety issues and possible opportunities for safety
improvements considering all roadway users. A Road Safety Audit was scheduled for the Five Corners
intersection because it was identified as a high crash location. Five Corners is scheduled to be
reconstructed in 2010 by the MassDOT Highway Division and is currently at the 100% design phase.
75% design plans were made available for review as part of the RSA. The RSA is intended to identify
both short and long term safety improvements that can be made along the subject corridor, which can then
be incorporated into the reconstruction project to the greatest extent practicable.
The Five Corners intersection of Foundry Street, Depot Street and Bay Road, shown in Figure 1, is
located in the southwestern portion of Easton. Though commonly referred to as a single intersection, Five
Corners consists of two separate closely spaced intersections. Foundry Street, Bay Road and Depot Street
form a 4-way, signalized intersection. Bay Road intersects Depot Street at an acute angle to form a T-
type unsignalized intersection approximately 125 feet north of the 4-way, signalized intersection.
Route 106 follows Foundry Street through the intersection, while Route 123 follows Foundry Street to the
west and Depot Street to the north as part of its overall southwest-northeast alignment. Route 106 is an
important regional roadway, connecting Easton with Mansfield to the west and West Bridgewater to the
east. Foundry Street provides access to Route 138 and has an interchange with Route 24 to the east.
Route 106 runs essentially parallel to I-495, and is known to serve as a cut-through for vehicles bound for
Route 24 and points north. Route 123 is also an important regional roadway, connecting Easton with
Norton and Attleboro to the southwest and Brockton to the northeast. Foundry Street, Depot Street and
Bay Road are all Town-owned roadways. Depot Street and Foundry Street are functionally classified as
an Urban Arterial, while Bay Road is classified as an Urban Collector.
Foundry Street is primarily one lane in each direction in the project vicinity, but widens to provide an 11
foot wide eastbound left turn lane onto Depot Street with approximately 300 feet of storage for queuing
vehicles and a 12 foot wide through lane for Foundry Street traffic. There is a small delta island that
channelizes the right turn movement from eastbound Foundry Street to Bay Road, which is under yield
control. The westbound Foundry Street approach is approximately 25 feet wide and provides a single
lane in each direction, and widens at the intersection to accommodate turning vehicles. The northbound
Bay Road approach is approximately 28 feet wide and provides a single lane in each direction. The
southbound Depot Street approach provides two lanes for the approximately 100 foot distance between
Bay Road and the stop line at Foundry Street, with a 12 foot wide exclusive right turn lane and a 12 foot
wide shared through and left turn lane. The two lanes are separated by a painted island.
Bay Road forms an acute angle with Depot Street and provides a single lane in each direction. The
northbound Depot Street lane is approximately 20 feet wide, and effectively provides the ability for
northbound vehicles to pass vehicles stopped to turn left onto Bay Road. The existing geometry requires
vehicles exiting Bay Road to cross the southbound right turn lane on Depot Street if they are intending to
continue south on Bay Road or turn left onto Foundry Street eastbound.
The land use of the surrounding area is primarily commercial. There are gas stations on the northeast,
southwest, and northwest corners of the 4-way signalized intersection, with an ATM kiosk on the
southeast corner. There is a CVS Pharmacy on the northern corner of the Bay Road/Depot Street
intersection, a Walgreens pharmacy adjacent to the Mobil station on the northwest corner, and a shopping
plaza with a Shaw’s supermarket north of the intersection. The gas station on the southwest corner has
internal connections to parking areas for several other auto-related businesses, which collectively share
three curb cuts along the eastbound Foundry Street approach.
The posted speed limit on Foundry Street in the vicinity of the intersection is 20 MPH. The speed limit
for Foundry Street increases to 40 MPH beyond the intersection in both directions. Speed data for the
intersection were provided by Old Colony Planning Council (OCPC), and were collected outside the 20
MPH speed zone. Speed data for Foundry Street eastbound approaching the intersection showed an

Crash data were collected and summarized by MassDOT for three years and are included in the
Appendix. There were a total of 33 crashes at the intersection within the period from January 2006 to
September 2008. 26 of these crashes are mapped on the collision diagram included in the Appendix. Ten
of the 26 mapped crashes involved vehicles either entering or exiting one of the curb cuts for the gas
station and other businesses on the southwest corner of the intersection. Eight of those ten crashes
specifically involved a collision between a westbound vehicle turning left and an eastbound vehicle. It
was noted during the audit meeting that 12 of the 33 crashes involved a teenage driver.

Automatic Traffic Recorder (ATR) counts and Manual Turning Movement (MTM) counts were provided
by OCPC. ATR data were recorded in 2006. Foundry Street carries 20,000 vehicles per day (vpd) west
of the Five Corners intersection and 12,800 vpd east of the intersection. Depot Street carries 18,000 vpd
north of the intersection. Bay Road carries 6,100 vpd south of the intersection, and 5,100 vpd north of the
intersection. MTM data were recorded in 2005 for both the morning and afternoon peak periods. The
morning peak hour occurred from 7:15 to 8:15 AM. There were 585 left turns from Foundry Street
eastbound to Depot Street, and 401 right turns in the opposite direction from Depot Street to Foundry
Street westbound during the AM peak hour. At the unsignalized intersection of Depot Street and Bay
Road, there were 192 vehicles turning left onto Bay Road and 713 vehicles continuing north on Depot
The afternoon peak hour occurred from 4:45 to 5:45 PM. During the afternoon peak hour, there were 440
left turns from Foundry Street eastbound to Depot Street, and 591 right turns in the opposite direction
from Depot Street to Foundry Street westbound. At the unsignalized intersection of Depot Street and Bay
Road, there were 123 vehicles turning left onto Bay Road and 541 vehicles continuing north on Depot
Street. Complete ATR and MTM count data are included in the Appendix.
Following a brief introduction to the RSA process and a summary of traffic volumes and crash
information, the audit participants were asked to discuss safety hazards at the Five Corners intersection.
Audit participants then conducted a site visit as a group, at which time they offered observations on safety
concerns and deficiencies. A summary of those major safety considerations is as follows:
Capacity – A number of safety concerns discussed at the audit were the result of existing traffic signal
operation and existing geometry. The lack of an exclusive left turn phase with an arrow indication for
the heavy eastbound left turn lane and the lack of storage room for northbound left turning vehicles
between Foundry Street and Bay Road were among the concerns.
Signal head alignment – It was noted by Town of Easton personnel that the existing signal heads
often become misaligned and require adjustment. This was observed during the audit site visit.
Lighting – Roadway lighting is limited in the project area, specifically along the south side of
Foundry Street. It was suggested that improved lighting at area businesses, including the Mobil gas
station, draws the driver’s focus away from the roadway which reduces driver awareness and
Access Management – The study area is comprised of closely spaced businesses with multiple curb
cuts. It was suggested during the audit that the heavy volume of traffic during peak periods is a
contributor towards the number of crashes involving turning vehicles, as increased delay may
encourage drivers to consider inadequate gaps.
Pedestrian accommodations – There are existing pedestrian signals and pedestrian pushbuttons at the
signalized intersection, but the lack of an exclusive pedestrian phase and the lack of sidewalks on
some approaches were noted as a safety concern.
Young drivers – It was mentioned at the audit that nearly one third of crashes involved teenagers.
The Southeastern Regional Vocational High School is approximately two miles east of the Five
Corners intersection on Foundry Street. A brief investigation of available data during the audit
showed no direct correlation between time of day and crashes involving teenagers.
Aesthetics – Although not specifically a safety concern, it was suggested during the audit that the
Five Corners intersection acts as a gateway to Easton from the west and the southwest, and that
landscaping improvements should be considered at the intersection.
Emergency Preemption – The Easton Fire Chief noted that there is no emergency preemption
equipment at the intersection, but that optical detectors that detect approaching emergency vehicles
should be considered in the design of planned improvements at the intersection. It should be noted

After the site visit, audit participants returned to the meeting location to discuss the safety issues and
consider improvements. Audit participants were encouraged to consider both short and long term
improvements for each issue. Each improvement considered has been categorized as short-term, mid-
term, or long-term based on the definitions shown in Table 2. Additionally, a cost category has been
assigned to each improvement based on the parameters set forth in Table 2.
Table 2. Estimated Time Frame and Costs Breakdown
The following improvements were suggested by audit participants to improve safety issues associated
Exclusive left turn phase. Signal upgrades planned for the Five Corners intersection should include
an exclusive advance left turn phase for vehicles turning from Foundry Street eastbound to Depot
Street. 75% design plans reviewed in advance of the audit include this phase. This is a mid-term,
low cost improvement if done in conjunction with already planned traffic signal improvements.
Increase capacity on Depot Street northbound between Foundry Street and Bay Road. The existing
geometry provides one wide northbound lane and only 100 feet of storage for left turning vehicles
between Foundry Street and Bay Road. 75% design plans reviewed in advance of the audit show two
general purpose lanes on this approach, which will allow left turning vehicles to queue in the left lane
while through vehicles can continue unimpeded in the right lane. The Bay Road approach to Depot
Street has been realigned so that Bay Road intersects Depot Street at a 90º angle. This realignment
increases the storage space between the intersections to approximately 180 feet. This is a mid-term,
low cost improvement if done in conjunction with already planned geometric improvements.
Timing improvements. It was suggested by an audit participant that signal timing improvements can
be made at the existing intersection in advance of the proposed reconstruction project. This is a short-
Install bracket mounted signal heads. Signal upgrades at the Five Corners intersection should include
bracket mounted signal heads instead of free-swinging signal heads. This will prevent the signal
heads from becoming misaligned due to wind as they do today. This is a mid-term, low cost
improvement if done in conjunction with already planned geometric improvements.
Upgrade lighting at the intersection. It was suggested that roadway lighting should be improved
along the along Foundry Street and at the Five Corners intersection. This improvement would
involve installing overhead lights on existing utility poles. This is a mid-term, medium cost
improvement. The Town of Easton would be responsible for paying utility costs.
Improve access management. There are a significant number of driveways and access points along
Foundry Street in the vicinity of the intersection, specifically at the southwest corner of the
intersection. Crash data show that these driveways create a safety issue due to the increased number
of turning movements and conflicts created with turning vehicles. It is recommended that the Town
of Easton verify permits against existing driveway openings and approach existing business owners
about combining or eliminating driveway openings, or designating enter and exit driveways with
signage for right turn only exiting. It was noted during the audit that the combination of driveways
could prove challenging because most businesses in the area are on separate parcels, even if they
share an internal connection. This is a short-term, low cost improvement that could be done in
Provide pedestrian accommodations. It is recommended that sidewalks be installed on all approaches
as part of the upcoming reconstruction project. In conjunction with that work, crosswalks, pedestrian
pushbuttons and an exclusive pedestrian phase should be provided at the signalized Five Corners
intersection. This is a mid-term, high cost improvement that should be done in conjunction with
Education. Due to the relatively high percentage of crashes involving teenage drives, education
should be used to increase awareness of the safety concerns at the intersection. The Easton Police
Department should work with students at the nearby Southeastern Regional Vocational High School,
as well as the Easton High School, in order to educate young drivers to exercise safe driving habits
throughout Easton. This is a short-term, low cost solution.
Install vegetation. Although not necessarily a safety improvement, the proposed design should
consider trees and shrubs as part of the proposed design. The designer should work closely with
MassDOT to insure that the style and/or placement of vegetation will not impede sight lines. This is a
mid-term, medium cost improvement if done in conjunction with already planned improvements. The
Town of Easton would be responsible for the cost.
Provide emergency preemption. The Town of Easton does not currently have optical emitter
equipment on its emergency vehicles, but plans to install equipment in the future. The proposed
design should include emergency preemption equipment as part of the proposed signal layout. 75%
design plans reviewed in advance of the audit included emergency preemption equipment. This is a
mid-term, medium cost improvement if done in conjunction with already planned geometric
Install no left turn sign or island. These were actions discussed at the audit as potential solutions to
prevent westbound Foundry Street vehicles from turning left into the gas station and other businesses
on the southwest corner of the intersection. It was believed that a sign would prove ineffective at
preventing left turns, and a barrier island would require additional widening beyond the extensive
widening already proposed to accommodate an additional turning lane for the Foundry Street
eastbound approach. As a result, this improvement is not recommended.
Table 3 summarizes potential recommendations discussed by the audit team. The recommendations are
categorized based on the potential safety payoff, as well as by time frame and cost. The safety payoff is a
qualitative judgment of the effectiveness of the potential safety improvements. Each recommendation has
a responsibility assigned to it stating whether MassDOT or the Town of Easton would be responsible for
implementing the recommended improvement. “Project” refers to improvements that are assumed to be
included or could reasonably be accommodated as part of the planned reconstruction of the intersection.
